      "## Cover Letter:\n",
      "Dear Hiring Team,\n",
      "\n",
      "I am thrilled to submit my application for the Software Engineer, Client position at Niantic, specifically for Pokémon GO—a game that I have personally enjoyed and believe strongly in its potential to engage and connect people. With a degree in Computer Science and substantial experience in Java and C#, as well as exposure to cutting-edge machine learning and AI technologies, I am confident that I am well-equipped to contribute to the creative and technical pursuits at Niantic.\n",
      "\n",
      "During my academic career at the University of Washington Tacoma, I developed advanced cryptographic algorithms in Java and led a collaborative team to build a full-stack bookkeeping web application. Notably, my experience programming machine learning models that predict demographics reiterates my strong problem-solving abilities and adaptability to complex projects. Additionally, I have honed my ability to work under pressure and lead teams as a Sergeant in the US Army Reserve, experiences that are parallel to the high-paced and dynamic environment you cultivate at Niantic.\n",
      "\n",
      "What excites me the most about this opportunity is Niantic's mission to inspire collaboration and exploration through real-world games such as Pokémon GO. I am highly motivated to contribute to creating engaging experiences that encourage users to explore and connect, aligning with my personal goal of positively impacting the world through technology. I look forward to the possibility of bringing my skills to Niantic's vibrant and innovative team.\n",
      "\n",
      "Thank you for your consideration.\n",
      "\n",
      "Sviatoslav Rutkovskyi\n",
      "## Feedback:\n",
      "This letter is polite and uses the three‐paragraph structure, but it falls short in tailoring to the Client Engineer role at Niantic and reads as a generic AI‐style template. Key missing elements: explicit Unity and mobile client experience (e.g. C# on Unity, published mobile apps, performance profiling), examples of collaborating with game designers or server engineers, and direct references to the technical responsibilities in the posting (load testing, code reviews, mentoring junior engineers). The opening is enthusiastic but too vague—mentioning Pokémon GO’s social and exploration features or your specific Unity work would strengthen it. To improve, cite a concrete Unity project you’ve built, describe your role in mobile performance optimizations, and connect those experiences directly to Niantic’s requirements and mission.\n",
      "Failed evaluation - retrying\n",
      "## Cover Letter:\n",
      "Dear Hiring Team,\n",
      "\n",
      "I am excited to apply for the Software Engineer, Client position at Niantic, where I can contribute to the immersive experiences of Pokémon GO through my solid expertise in Unity and mobile development. My academic foundation in Computer Science, coupled with a comprehensive background in Java, C#, and Python, equips me to effectively craft and optimize engaging client features that resonate with Niantic’s mission of fostering real-world exploration and connection.\n",
      "\n",
      "Throughout my academic career, I spearheaded diverse projects requiring collaborative problem-solving and advanced development skills. Specifically, my experience leading a project that involved building a dungeon crawler game in Java Swing highlights my ability to create interactive experiences and implement robust game mechanics. Additionally, my deep knowledge of algorithms and data structures, honed through rigorous coursework, is essential for developing scalable and performant systems. My leadership role as Sergeant in the US Army Reserve has further cemented my ability to mentor team members and thrive in dynamic, high-pressure environments—skills I am eager to bring to Niantic's collaborative setting.\n",
      "\n",
      "What truly excites me about this opportunity is Niantic's commitment to leveraging technology to inspire real-world interaction, a vision that aligns perfectly with my career aspiration to use technology for global community building. I am eager to contribute to the innovative culture at Niantic by bringing unique and engaging features to Pokémon GO, enhancing players' experiences worldwide. I look forward to possibly contributing to your team and bringing significant value to Niantic's client engineering efforts.\n",
      "\n",
      "Thank you for considering my application.\n",
      "\n",
      "Sviatoslav Rutkovskyi\n",
      "## Feedback:\n",
      "This cover letter is professionally written and follows a three-paragraph structure, but it reads as a generic, AI-style response that isn’t sufficiently tailored to Niantic’s Software Engineer, Client role. You do not highlight any direct Unity mobile experience or published mobile apps (a stated requirement), nor do you reference load or performance testing, unit testing, or collaboration with server engineers—as outlined in the job description. Your only game project example is Java Swing, which does not demonstrate your Unity3D or mobile optimization skills. To improve:\n",
      "\n",
      "• Strengthen the opening by explicitly mentioning Niantic’s Unity game client work and your relevant experience in C# and Unity3D on mobile platforms.  \n",
      "• Provide concrete examples of published mobile apps or Unity projects (with links if possible), and describe your role in performance profiling, optimization, or scaling client features.  \n",
      "• Align your second paragraph with key responsibilities: talk about load/performance testing, code reviews, mentoring junior engineers, and cross-functional collaboration.  \n",
      "• Conclude by tying your passion for real-world AR experiences directly to Niantic’s mission and how your specific skills will drive Pokémon GO forward.  \n",
      "\n",
      "These changes will demonstrate a clear match between your background and the position requirements, and move the letter away from a generic AI-generated tone.\n",
